{#- One blueprint serves all four arc-functions. Pick the human name, the LaTeX
    command, and whether the argument is bounded to [-1, 1] (arcsin/arccos) or
    accepts any real value (arctg/arcctg). The argument `value` is mapped from its
    plain form to clean LaTeX. -#}
{%- set names = {'arcsin': 'арксинуса', 'arccos': 'арккосинуса', 'arctg': 'арктангенса', 'arcctg': 'арккотангенса'} -%}
{%- set latex = {'arcsin': '\\arcsin', 'arccos': '\\arccos', 'arctg': '\\operatorname{arctg}', 'arcctg': '\\operatorname{arcctg}'} -%}
{%- set vals = {'0': '0', '1/2': '\\frac{1}{2}', 'sqrt(2)/2': '\\frac{\\sqrt{2}}{2}', 'sqrt(3)/2': '\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}', '1': '1', 'sqrt(3)': '\\sqrt{3}'} -%}
{%- set bounded = func_type in ['arcsin', 'arccos'] -%}
PROBLEM TO POSE (turn ONLY this into the word problem; keep every number exactly as written):
- Expression: y = {{ func_type }}({{ value }})
- Ask the student to compute the value of the {{ names[func_type] }} using the table of
  standard angles (the answer is an angle in RADIANS), and to state the domain and range
  of this function.

=== INTERNAL (guidance for you only — never show, restate, paraphrase, number, or hint any of this to the student) ===
- Key facts to recall: {{
    'this is an inverse of a bounded function, so its argument lives in a closed segment'
    if bounded else
    'this is an inverse of an unbounded function, so its argument may be ANY real number' }};
  the result is always an angle measured in radians, never in degrees.
- Render all math as LaTeX inside $...$ (e.g. $y = {{ latex[func_type] }}{{ '{' }}{{ vals[value] }}{{ '}' }}$).
- Do NOT state or hint at the answer: the resulting angle, the domain, or the range of
  the {{ names[func_type] }} must NOT be given to the student.
